              "The Seoul Olympic Museum of Art (SOMA) has routinely held exhibitions titled Artists Rediscovered, the first of which was Jooho Kim, Hanjin Park, Kunyong Lee &mdash;Restless Hand, Unfixed Spirit. These exhibitions including Sunghy Shin&mdash;Soonja Han (2009) and TchahSup Kim, Soocheon Jheon, Ai Kyu Hahn &mdash;Deep Breath (2014) have been continuously organized in the form of a two-man or three-man exhibition. This type of art show has given prominence to both the spirit of artists and the spirit of the times through works by artists who are deemed worthy of having their art re-examined from the perspective of contemporary Korean art trends. Such an exhibition was also designed to take a closer look at an artist&rsquo;s worldview and art world in the form of a retrospective from Changbae Hwang &mdash;The Tent of Delights in 2018. This year&rsquo;s Artists Rediscovered exhibition is intended to lay out the story of In Ryu (July 20, 1956-January 11, 1999), a sculptural genius who died at a young age. 2019 marks 20 years since he has passed. In the winter of 1999, a roaring artistic soul died away in a flurry. A graduate of sculpture from Hongik University and its graduate school, Ryu gained a reputation as a distinguished sculptor of figurative Korean sculpture while tackling the human body in a traditional manner coupled with contemporary expression. While accomplishing his artistic feats, he passed away at the young age of 43. He left behind approximately 70 sculptures and installations that were made over the course of 10 years, a relatively short period in terms of artistic activities. This exhibition comprehensively covers the entirety of his artistic practices. It spans 15 years from the period when he first began his artistic activities in earnest with his winning of a special prize at the Korean Mokwoohoe Fine Art Association Contest in 1983 to the suspension of his work in 1997 due to bad health. It also features diverse archived materials that provide a glimpse of his concerns about and experimentations with the themes he had delved into throughout his life. In short, the exhibition consists of five themes that pigeonhole In Ryu&rsquo;s works: From Clay, Entering the Mountains&mdash;Descending the Mountains, The Stage of Life, Portraits of Contemporaries, and The Spirit of a Sculptor. The artist expressed his ideas about his work through his interviews with the press and contributions to the media over the course of his lifetime. His statements, which could be references for each theme, were extracted from his interviews to help understand and appreciate his pieces. If we were to appreciate his works while reflecting on his statements, his serious and blind aspiration for sculpture would be conveyed by the way it deeply resonates with our hearts. On display in the archive space are various aspects of his life and art as exemplified by multiple types of materials, such as drawings and maquettes for coming up with works, notes that showcase his studies of anatomy, replicas of his hand made before and after his death, books and newspapers he referred to while working, and news articles and TV broadcasting videos featuring his life and art. ",
